plechase of those years into a powerful "heroic moment." He breaks new ground by linking the era’s "new imperialism" to its "new journalism"—the penny press—which furnished the public with larger-than-life figures who then embodied each nation’s imperial hopes and anxieties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aExplorerszAfricavBiography. 0aExplorerszEuropevBiography. 0aMass mediazFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMass mediazGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aafrican history.  abritain.  acharles gordon.  acolonial heroes.  acolonialism.  acomparative history.  aconquest.  afrance.  aglobal empires.  ahenry morton stanley.  ahistorians.  ahistorical perspective.  ahubert lyautey.  aimperial history.  aimperial hopes.  aimperialism.  aindigenous peoples.  ajean baptiste marchand.  anationalism.  anew imperialism.  anew journalism.  anonfiction.  apenny press.  apierre savorgnan de brazza.  aretrospective.  avanquishing hero.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023427740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094719140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947191423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947191/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY